		{"id":"3cd11c6e0ae8c4c6","type":"text","text":"## Configure SSH Login Alerts Email Notification\nWe need `mailx` and `sendmail` package for sending mail\n\n```\n1. yum install -y mailx sendmail\n2. systemctl start sendmail\n3. systemctl enable sendmail\n4. systemctl status sendmail\n\n------------ now we need to entry in /root/.bashrc file ------------\n\n1. vim /root/.bashrc\n---- echo ALERT - Root Shell Access \"$HOSTNAME\" on: `date` `who` | mail -s \"Alert: Root Access\" root@localhost ------\n\nðŸ‘¾ðŸ‘¾ The entry inside .bashrc is self explainatry here :\n------ echo ALERT - Root Shell Access \"$HOSTNAME\" on: `date` `who` is the Alert message --------\n\n------ mail -s \"Alert: Root Access\" root@localhost this is the mail we are sending and -s is for subject ------\nhere root@localhost is the email on which we want to send the mail you can use aditya@gmail.com instead root@localhost\n\n2. Now any individual login with root user get the mail \n```\n\n```\n1. mail \nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ You will see no mail is for root yet because no one is loggined yet using root previllage\n\n2. tail -f /var/log/maillog\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ Will show you the mail logs\n```\n\n```\n1. source .bashrc\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ when we login this file will execute so we directly executing it for seeing whether mail is sent or not. \nOn doing that you will see the mail sent on root@localhost /var/spool/mail/root location and also you can see in /var/log/mailog file\n\n2. mail \nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ These will also shows you the sent and recieved mail\n```","x":-1030,"y":-280,"width":1190,"height":920,"color":"3"},
		{"id":"3854d44dd956c08d","type":"text","text":"# SSHPass\nIt is the utility that help you to give password with SSH login in single command\nYou need `epel-release` repository to be configured in you machine then you need `sshpass` package \n\n```\n1. yum install epel-release\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ It will install and configured epel-release repository\n\n2. yum repolist all\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ Will show epel-release repository if successfully installed and configured\n\n3. yum -y install sshpass\n\n4. sshpass -h \nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ -h meaning help it will tell what are the options do we have for these command\n```\n\n### Usage\n\n```\n1. sshpass -p 'my-password' ssh 192.168.0.164 -l root -o StrictHostKeyChecking=no\n\nlet's break it\n\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ -p 'my-password' ---> here -p stands for password which is 'my-password'\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ ssh 192.168.0.164 -l root ---> here 192.168.0.164 is IP and root is user-name\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ -o StrictHostKeyChecking=no ---> -o stands for options  \n```\n\n```\n2. sshpass -p 'my-password' ssh 192.168.0.164 -l root -o StrictHostKeyChecking=no \n\"uptime; username -a\"\n\nyou can run many commands while SSH like we are doing here \"uptime; username -a\" \n```\n\n#### SSH with coping file using SSHPass\n\n```\n1. sshpass -p 'my-password' rsync -av --progress myfile.tar.gz root@192.168.0.131:/tmp/\n\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ Here myfile.tar.gz file is copying on path /tmp\n```\n\n### SSH using SSHPass with providing password using file\n\n```\n1. vim mypass.txt\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ my-password\n----------------here my-password is the content that we entered inside mypass.txt --------\n\n2. sshpass -f 'mypass.txt' ssh 192.168.0.164 -l root -o StrictHostKeyChecking=no\n```","x":200,"y":-280,"width":860,"height":1260,"color":"4"},
